{{>header}}

<h1>Sample Page</h1>
<div class="mt-5 mb-5">
  <h4>JSON data</h4>
  <p> Quest Log pages can read any data you add to ./site.json, in addition you can add json files with the same names as your pages in ./src/pages, for example this sample-page.hbs has a companion sample-page.json which is accessible by <em>any
      page</em> via it's name; in this case 'samplePage'. If your page/json file combo have spaces or dashes in them, the name of the data will be in camelCase. For example: <em>stroopwafel.json</em> becomes <em>stroopwafel</em>, and
    <em>bagel-funtime.json</em> becomes <em>bagelFuntime</em>.

    <h5>Example of content from JSON</h5>
    <div class="row">
      <div class="col-sm-6">
        <p>Code:</p>
        <xmp>{{#raw}}
  <p>Characters:</p>
  <ul>
    [[#each samplePage.characters]]
    <li>[[this]]</li>
    [[/each]]
  </ul>
          {{/raw}}</xmp>

      </div>
      <div class="col-sm-6">
              <p>Result:</p>
        <p>Characters:</p>
        <ul>
          {{#each samplePage.characters}}
            <li>{{this}}</li>
          {{/each}}
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>


</div>

<div class="mt-5 mb-5">
  <h4>Bootstrap</h4>
  <p>Quest Log uses Bootstrap, find out all you can do with Bootstrap here: <a href="https://getbootstrap.com/docs/4.3/getting-started/introduction/" target="_blank">https://getbootstrap.com/docs/4.3/getting-started/introduction/</a>
    <em>If you wish to remove Bootstrap; you can find it in ./src/partials/header.hbs and ./src/partials/footer.hbs</em></p>

  <p>You can also use Handlebars features in pages, each page is fed data from a coorisponding JSON file of the same name (see the 'sample-page.json' file in the same folder as this file)</p>
</div>


